    "Here's what I found:\n\nThe OUI `C4:3C:B0` is registered to **Shenzhen Bilian Electronic Co., Ltd**. They're a Chinese ODM/OEM manufacturer that makes Wi-Fi and Bluetooth modules. They don't sell consumer products directly — their chips end up inside other brands' devices.\n\nCommon products that use Bilian modules include:\n- Smart home devices (smart plugs, bulbs, switches)\n- IoT sensors and hubs\n- IP cameras\n- Smart speakers\n- Appliances with Wi-Fi connectivity (robot vacuums, air purifiers, etc.)\n\nSince it's on your IoT VLAN, think about any smart home gear you've recently added — a smart plug, a Tuya/SmartLife device, or something similar. Bilian modules are very commonly found in Tuya-based products.\n\nIf you want to narrow it down further, you could:\n- Check the IP/hostname in your network monitor dashboard or DHCP leases — the hostname sometimes reveals the device type\n- Cross-reference the IP with your router's ARP table to see which port/AP it's connected to, which might help locate it physically\n- Check if the device responds to common discovery protocols: `nmap -sV <ip>` can sometimes identify the service/device type\n\nReferences:\n[1] MAC Address Vendor Lookup - https://maclookup.app/search/result?mac=C4:3C:B0:5D:BA:9A\n[Tool uses: none]",
